      h2 Layout managers
      ul
        li An important part of designing a GUI application is determining the layout of the components
          ul
            li In Java we are not supposed to specify the exact location of a component within a window (although possible)
            li Instead we should use a layout manager
            li The layout manager will help control the positions and sizes of components, and makes adjustments when necessary (e.g. when the size of a window is changed)
        li Java provides several different layout managers, useful for different situations
    section
      h2 Layout managers
      div.small-text
        ul
          li Four of the most commonly used layout managers:
            ul
              li.
                FlowLayout - Simply arranges components horizontally in a row. If there
                is not room for all components in one row, they are distributed across
                multiple rows. (default for JPanel objects)
              li BoxLayout - Either places all components horizontally next to each other in a row, or vertically below each other:
                ul
                  li BoxLayout.X_AXIS or BoxLayout.Y_AXIS
              li BorderLayout - Arranges components in five regions: (default for JFrame objects)
                ul
                  li North, South, East, West, and Center
              li GridLayout - Arranges components in a grid with rows and columns
    section
      h2 Layout managers
      ul
        li A layout manager is added to a component by calling the setLayout method
          ul
            li We can add a layout manager to any of the GUI classes that are used to contain other components - e.g. JFrame and JPanel
            li In a GUI class that extends JFrame we could set the layout of its content pane by calling setLayout in the constructor
  section
    section
      h2 Flow layout
      ul.small-text
        li Components will be placed horizontally, from left to right, in the order that they were added
        li When there is no more room in a row, the next components “flow” to the next row
        li we can also align all components to the right if we like
      div.split-2-3-left
        pre
          code.java.
            //flowlayout is default for JPanels
            JPanel pnl1 = new JPanel();
            JButton btn1 = new JButton("Button 1");
            pnl1.add(btn1);
            JButton btn2 = new JButton("Button 2");
            pnl1.add(btn2);
            JButton btn3 = new JButton("Button 3");
            pnl1.add(btn3);
            JButton btn4 = new JButton("Button 4");
            pnl1.add(btn4);
            JButton btn5 = new JButton("Button 5");
            pnl1.add(btn5);
            //the line below align all components to the right if uncommented
            //pnl1.setLayout(new FlowLayout(FlowLayout.RIGHT));
      div.split-1-3-right
